4.
 Discussion
Recent
 epidemiological
 data
 have
 associated
 T2DM
 with
 an
increased
 risk
 of
 developing
 mild
 cognitive
 impairment
 as
 well
as
 AD
 [44]. Therefore,
 the
 possibility
 of
 preventing
 the
 develop-
ment
 of
 such
 comorbidity
 in
 diabetic
 patients
 is
 a
 great
 research
and
 therapeutic
 challenge.
 In
 this
 light,
 the
 increasing
 knowledge
about
 the
 role
 of
 GLP-1
 and
 its
 receptors
 in
 the
 CNS
 is
 very
 inter-
esting,
 where
 they
 seem
 to
 have
 a
 key
 role
 in
 promoting
 cellular
growth
 and
 reducing
 apoptosis
 besides
 other
 effects
 including
a
 role
 in
 cognitive
 decline.
 For
 example,
 pre-clinical
 data
 have
demonstrated
 signiﬁcant
 neuroprotective
 effects
 of
 GLP-1
 ago-
nists
 in
 models
 of
 AD,
 by
 reducing
 –amyloid
 plaques,
 preventing
loss
 of
 synapses
 and
 memory
 impairment,
 and
 reducing
 oxidative
166
 
